{"@type":"Process","@id":"a413e897-b16e-4d66-9f4a-28c1c0f7bdfb","name":"Inverter; at plant; 500 W","description":"\"This cradle-to-gate unit process dataset is for the production of 1 unit of 500 W inverter.\nThis unit process includes raw material acquisition; manufacturing; transport; production and use of electricity; disposal of process waste; recovery of used products via reuse, recycling, and energy recovery ancillary materials manufacturing; manufacture and installation of capital equipment. The end-of-life of the product itself is included in the model.\"","category":"31-33: Manufacturing/3353: Electric Equipment Manufacturing","version":"00.00.076","lastChange":"2025-07-17T18:16:30.402Z","processType":"UNIT_PROCESS","isInfrastructureProcess":false,"location":{"@type":"Location","@id":"1a13105b-7e4e-35fb-ae7c-9515ac06aa48","name":"Netherlands","category":"Country"},"processDocumentation":{"validFrom":"2000-01-01","validUntil":"2004-12-31","timeDescription":"De-Wild Scholten (2007), which is the source used in Jungbluth et al. (2012), indicated the calendar years 2000-2004 as time period. Exact dates are assumed.","geographyDescription":"Inventory is based on the PSI 300 from Philips, which may be manufactured in Eindhoven. De Wild-Scholten (2007 indicated that the geography was for Western Europe, but supranational geographies do not work well with regionalized Life Cycle Impact Assessment Methods.","technologyDescription":"\"This process represent the production of micro solar inverters using average technology for Europe from the calendar years 2000-2004.\n\"\"Inverters consist of  transformer, electronic components as control units, a case and some connectors (Jungbluth et al., 2012).  In addition to the inverter assembly, the inventory includes external packaging and the disposal of production waste and of the inverter itself at the end of life.\"","inventoryMethodDescription":"Attributional cradle-to-grave.","modelingConstantsDescription":"Jungbluth et al. (2012) a standard distance of 60 km is assumed for truck transport,  200 km for train transport, and 18000 km of transoceanic transport. ","completenessDescription":"Treatment of Missing Environmental Data\r\nJungbluth et al. (2012) offered no information on cutoff criteria or flows that might have not been considered.\r\n\r\nTreatment of Missing Technosphere Data\r\nJungbluth et al. (2012) offered no information on cutoff criteria or flows that might have not been considered.\r\n\r\nMass Balance\r\nNo mass balance was calculated for this process.","dataSelectionDescription":"This unit process was modeled based on Jungbluth et al. (2012) inventory for a 500 W inverter,  available on Table 11.25 of said report.","dataTreatmentDescription":"The values in the LCI in Jungbluth et al. (2012) reflect the expert judgement of the authors. An important fraction of all data comes from one manufacturer and one kind of inverter only. ","samplingDescription":"System boundary conditions\r\nThe system boundary is cradle to grave and includes direct emissions, material and energy use, transport, waste treatment (of waste generated during production and of the final product) and infrastructure.\r\n\r\nData collection\r\nThe inventory present in  Jungbluth et al. (2012) was based on the production of one inverter, as collected by De Wild-Scholten (2007). \r\n\r\nUncertainty\r\nJungbluth et al. (2012)) included a standard deviation for all exchanges, which is repeated here.\"","dataCollectionDescription":"Data was collected during the calendar years 2000-2004, as indicated in de Wild-Scholten (2007)","useAdvice":"None.","sources":[{"@type":"Source","@id":"2b683923-b652-45fe-90a2-ecacfe957cb6","name":"de Wild-Scholten and Alsema (2007) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"},{"@type":"Source","@id":"d0a88c20-fd4e-42f6-abb8-cd60183d0fd5","name":"Jungbluth et al. (2012) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"}],"flowCompleteness":[{"aspect":"Freshwater ecotoxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Renewable primary energy consumption","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Ozone depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Noise","value":"Relevant flows missing"},{"aspect":"Non-renewable primary energy depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Acidification","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Human toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Species depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Land use","value":"Relevant flows missing"},{"aspect":"Non-renewable material resource depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Eutrophication","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Particulate matter/respiratory inorganics","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Climate change","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Seawater eco-toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Summer smog","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Terrestric eco-toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Renewable material resource consumption","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Product model","value":"All relevant flows quantified"},{"aspect":"Radioactivity","value":"No statement"}],"reviews":[{"reviewType":"Independent external review","scopes":[{"name":"Documentation","methods":["Validation of data sources"]}],"details":"Colleagues at the Paul Scherrer Institute are acknowledged for their revision of data, but no other details on their review are available.  Because it is not properly documented, the \"Process review\" data quality entry is left as \"5: Not documented\"","assessment":[],"reviewers":[{"@type":"Actor","@id":"9828dc79-762c-4234-b044-f6be9d66fa7b","name":"Paul Scherrer Institute","category":"Organisations"}]},{"reviewType":"Dependent internal review","scopes":[{"name":"Documentation","methods":["Validation of data sources"]}],"details":"Colleagues at ESU-services Ldt. are acknowledged for their revision of data, but no other details on their review are available. Because it is not properly documented, the \"Process review\" data quality entry is left as \"5: Not documented\".","assessment":[],"reviewers":[{"@type":"Actor","@id":"d964d915-2173-468a-a219-76387c5edb45","name":"ESU-services Ltd.","category":"Organisations"}]}],"intendedApplication":"\"Situation C2 - Accounting, without system-external interactions - The intended application is a purely descriptive accounting / documentation of the analyzed system excluding interactions with other systems in the LCI model.\nThe target audience of this model are LCA practitioners, the silicon, solar and related industries and the general public. The inventory is considered largely complete, except for land transformation activities. For that reason, it is not recommended to use this dataset when evaluating land use impact categories. The results of the National Institute of Standards and Technology’s data gap analysis were analyzed using the ISO 21930-LCIA-US impact assessment methodology, as well as Cumulative Energy Demand and a subset of ReCiPe 2016 impact categories.\nThe original application of this dataset was the identification of data gaps in the Federal LCA Commons (FLCAC) (see \"\"Project\"\" above). However, the intended application is to provide a cradle-to-gate inventory (A1-A3, according to ISO 21930) using exclusively processes currently available in USLCI or generated as part of the project mentioned above, and elementary flows from the Federal Elementary Flow List (FEDEFL) to enable the use of a fuller range of LCIA impact categories than those reported in EPDs. For data quality purposes, the intended application is to provide a US average inventory for the year of publication of the original source.\"","projectDescription":"This dataset was developed as part of the “Public Life Cycle Inventory Data Gap Analysis for Silicon-based Residential Photovoltaic Systems” National Institute of Standards and Technology’s Technical Note.","dataGenerator":{"@type":"Actor","@id":"dd386adb-2c05-4de6-8317-63943d599a8b","name":"Gonzalo Rodriguez-Garcia","category":"Persons"},"dataDocumentor"